            &lt;p&gt;Ah, I misinterpreted.  In that case, I would guess your sampling bias&lt;br&gt;
is up to the gods as much as it is for any random population.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
On Jan 4, 2008 12:38 PM, afcarl2 &lt;&lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;mailto:a.carl%40ngc.com&quot;&gt;a.carl@...&lt;/a&gt;&gt; wrote:&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; Cherry-picking a single best population, one of many. NOT creating a&lt;br&gt;
&gt; population composed of best individuals from multiple populations.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; Though that could be a next step.&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; --- In &lt;a target=&quot;_blank&quot; href=&quot;mailto:neat%40yahoogroups.com&quot;&gt;neat@yahoogroups.&lt;wbr&gt;com&lt;/a&gt;, &quot;Daniel Tuohy&quot; &lt;danielr2e@.&lt;wbr&gt;..&gt; wrote:&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; Cherry-picking the most-fit solutions from a random set of initial&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; solutions seems equivalent to bootstrapping NEAT with random search.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; Random search is inferior to genetic search for most domains to&lt;br&gt;
&gt; which&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; you would apply NEAT, so intuitively I would think that you wouldn&#39;t&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; see a tangible benefit from this approach. In fact, you could be&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; introducing damaging sampling bias by pointing NEAT away from optima&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; that might be too small to hit with the initial population, but may&lt;br&gt;
&gt; be&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; reachable from initial low-fit individuals.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; My guess is that you won&#39;t do any harm, but nor will you see&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; improvement. It&#39;s easy enough to test, though, so give it a shot.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; My&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; intuitions are wrong often enough.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; On Jan 3, 2008 6:45 PM, afcarl2 &lt;a.carl@...&gt; wrote:&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; Is there any significance to the composition of generation zero&lt;br&gt;
&gt; beyond&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; that of providing a radomized evaluation/starting point of the&lt;br&gt;
&gt; design&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; space? If the composition is a set of random points in the design&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; space, is one population/set of random starting points any&lt;br&gt;
&gt; different&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; than any other, except for perhaps getting lucky in regards to a&lt;br&gt;
&gt; higher&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; fitness potential via complexification?&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; The function of the NEAT params are focused on transition to&lt;br&gt;
&gt; subsequent&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; generations, and as such appear neutral wrt generation zero,&lt;br&gt;
&gt; except for&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; perhaps population size.&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; If this is the case, is there any loss of generality by generating&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; multiple populations of generation zero, and cherry-picking the&lt;br&gt;
&gt; best as&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt; the population to proceed with NEAT evolution?&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
&gt; &gt;&lt;br&gt;
